                                            Mean-Value Theorem

                                            5.10

                                            Given a function f defined and having a finite derivative in (a,b) and such that limx→b−f(x)=+∞. Prove that limx→b−f′(x) either fails to exist or is infinite.

                                            Proof

                                            Assume limx→b−f′(x)=A with |A|<∞, then ∃δ>0 such that whenever b−δ<x<b, we have |f′(x)−A|<1, or A−1<f′(x)<A+1. Since limx→b−f(x)=+∞, we can find a point y∈(b−δ,b) such that f(y)≥f(b−δ)+(A+1)δ, By Mean-Value theorem, there exists a ξ∈(b−δ,y) such that

                                            f′(ξ)=f(y)−f(b−δ)y−(b−δ)>f(y)−f(b−δ)δ=A+1

                                            this is a contradiction.

                                            5.11

                                            Show that the formula in the Mean-Value Theorem can be written as follows:

                                            f(x+h)−f(x)h=f′(x+θh),

                                            where 0<θ<1. Determine θ as a function of x and h when

                                            (a) f(x)=x2

                                            (b) f(x)=x3

                                            (c) f(x)=ex

                                            (d) f(x)=log⁡x,x>0.

                                            Keep x≠0 fixed, and find limh→0θ in each case.

                                            Solution

                                            In the Mean-Value Theorem, let a=x,b=x+h, then

                                            f(b)−f(a)=f′(c)(b−a),c∈(a,b)

                                            can be written as

                                            f(x+h)−f(x)=f′(c)h,c∈(x,x+h)

                                            write c=x+θh with 0<θ<1, we have

                                            f(x+h)−f(x)h=f′(x+θh),0<θ<1

                                            (a) We have f′(x)=2x, thus

                                            f(x+h)−f(x)h=2x+h,f′(x+θh)=2x+2θh

                                            so θ=1/2, and limh→0θ=1/2.

                                            (b) We have f′(x)=3x2, thus

                                            f(x+h)−f(x)h=3x2+3xh+h2,f′(x+θh)=3(x+θh)2

                                            write x/h=y, the equation becomes y+θ=±y2+y+1/3. Notice that h should be close to 0, thus y tends to be large, so when x>0, θ=y2+y+1/3−y and when x<0, θ=−y2+y+1/3−y, when x=0, we have θ=1/3 and limh→0θ=1/3. And we have when x>0:

                                            limh→0θ=limy→+∞(y2+y+1/3−y)=limy→+∞y+1/3y2+y+1/3+y=12

                                            and when x<0:

                                            limh→0θ=limy→−∞(−y2+y+1/3−y)=limy→−∞y+1/3y−y2+y+1/3=12

                                            thus limh→0θ=1/2 when x≠0.

                                            (c) We have f′(x)=ex, thus

                                            f(x+h)−f(x)h=ex+h−exh=ex(eh−1h)=ex+θh⟹θ=1hlog⁡eh−1h

                                            and

                                            limh→0θ=limh→0ehh−eh+1h(eh−1)=limh→0ehheh−1+heh=limh→0ehh+eh2eh+heh=12

                                            (d) We have f(x)=log⁡x and f′(x)=1/x, thus

                                            f(x+h)−f(x)h=1hlog⁡(1+hx)=1x+θh⟹θ=1log⁡(1+h/x)−xhlimh→0θ=limy→01log⁡(1+y)−1y=limy→0y−log⁡(1+y)ylog⁡(1+y)=limy→01−11+ylog⁡(1+y)+y1+y=limy→0y(1+y)log⁡(1+y)+y=limy→011+log⁡(1+y)+1=12

                                            5.12

                                            Take f(x)=3x4−2x3−x2+1 and g(x)=4x3−3x2−2x in Theorem 5.20. Show that f′(x)/g′(x) is never equal to the quotient [f(1)−f(0)]/[g(1)−g(0)] if 0<x≤1. How do you reconcile this with the equation

                                            f(b)−f(a)g(b)−g(a)=f′(x1)g′(x1),a<x1<b,

                                            obtainable from Theorem 5.20 when n=1?

                                            Solution

                                            First [f(1)−f(0)]/[g(1)−g(0)]=0. Since f′(x)=12x3−6x2−2x and g′(x)=12x2−6x−2, so if 0<x≤1, we have

                                            f′(x)g′(x)=12x3−6x2−2x12x2−6x−2=x>0=f(1)−f(0)g(1)−g(0)

                                            Theorem 5.20 when n=1 gives

                                            [f(x)−f(c)]g′(x1)=[g(x)−g(c)]f′(x1),x1∈(c,x)

                                            let x=1,c=0, then we have [f(1)−f(0)]g′(x1)=[g(1)−g(0)]f′(x1), and only when g′(x1)≠0 can we have

                                            f(1)−f(0)g(1)−g(0)=f′(x1)g′(x1)

                                            In fact, choose ξ∈(0,1) such that g′(ξ)=0, then f′(ξ)=ξg′(ξ)=0, which satisfies Theorem 5.20. That ξ must exists can be seen from g′(0)=−2<0,g′(1)=4>0 and g′ is continuous on [0,1].

                                            5.13

                                            In each of the following special cases of Theorem 5.20, take n=1,c=a,x=b and show that x1=(a+b)/2.

                                            (a) f(x)=sin⁡x,g(x)=cos⁡x;

                                            (b) f(x)=ex,g(x)=e−x.

                                            Can you find a general class of such pairs of functions f and g for which x1 will always be (a+b)/2 and such that both examples (a) and (b) are in this class?

                                            Solution

                                            (a) We suppose a<b, and (sin⁡b−sin⁡a)(−sin⁡x1)=(cos⁡b−cos⁡a)cos⁡x1 with x1∈(a,b) means

                                            tan⁡x1=−cos⁡b−cos⁡asin⁡b−sin⁡a=−2sin⁡a−b2sin⁡a+b2−2cos⁡a+b2sin⁡a−b2=tan⁡a+b2

                                            (b) We suppose a<b, and we have

                                            (eb−ea)(−e−x1)=(e−b−e−a)ex1,x1∈(a,b)

                                            this means

                                            e2x1=−eb−eae−b−e−a=−ea+beb−eaea−eb=ea+b⟹x1=a+b2

                                            5.14

                                            Given a function f defined and having a finite derivative f′ in the half-open interval 0<x<1 and such that |f′(x)|<1. Define an=f(1/n) for n=1,2,3,… , and show that limn→∞an exists.

                                            Proof

                                            Let ∀ε>0, there exists N>0 such that ε>1/N, for m>n>N, we have

                                            |an−am|=|f(1n)−f(1m)|=|f′(x)(1n−1m)|<|1n−1m|<1n<ε

                                            thus {an} is a Cauchy sequence.

                                            5.15

                                            Assume that f has a finite derivative at each point of the open interval (a,b). Assume also that limx→cf′(x) exists and is finite for some interior point c. Prove that the value of this limit must be f′(c).

                                            Proof

                                            We have

                                            f′(c)=limx→cf(x)−f(c)x−c=limx→cf′(y)(x−c)x−c=limx→cf′(y)

                                            for some y between x and c, when x→c, we have y→c, and the conclusion follows.

                                            5.16

                                            Let f be continuous on (a,b) with a finite derivative f′ everywhere in (a,b), except possibly at c. If limx→cf′(x) exists and has the value A, show that f′(c) must also exist and have the value A.

                                            Proof

                                            We have

                                            limx→cf(x)−f(c)x−c=limx→cf′(y)(x−c)x−c=limx→cf′(y)

                                            for some y between x and c, when x→c, we have y→c, and limx→cf′(y)=A, thus

                                            limx→cf(x)−f(c)x−c=A

                                            which implies f′(c) exists and f′(c)=A.

                                            5.17

                                            Let f be continuous on [0,1], f(0)=0, f′(x) finite for each x in (0,1). Prove that if f′ is an increasing function on (0,1), then so too is the function g defined by the equation g(x)=f(x)/x.

                                            Proof

                                            for any x∈(0,1) we can find some c∈(0,x) such that

                                            f(x)=f(x)−f(0)=f′(c)(x−0)=xf′(c)

                                            so for this x, we have

                                            g′(x)=xf′(x)−f(x)x2=xf′(x)−xf′(c)x2=1x(f′(x)−f′(c))≥0

                                            since x>c>0 and f′ is increasing. Thus g is increasing.

                                            5.18

                                            Assume f has a finite derivative in (a,b) and is continuous on [a,b] with f(a)=f(b)=0. Prove that for every real λ there is some c in (a,b) such that f′(c)=λf(c).

                                            Proof

                                            Let g(x)=e−λx and define F(x)=g(x)f(x), which is continuous on [a,b] and F(a)=F(b)=0, by Roll's theorem, there exist c∈(a,b) such that F′(c)=0, which means

                                            −λe−λcf(c)+e−λcf′(c)=0⟹f′(c)=λf(c)

                                            5.19

                                            Assume f is continuous on [a,b] and has a finite second derivative f″ in the open interval (a,b). Assume that the line segment joining the points A=(a,f(a)) and B=(b,f(b)) intersects the graph of f in a third point P different from A and B. Prove that f″(c)=0 for some c in (a,b).

                                            Proof

                                            The line joining A and B can be written as

                                            y−f(a)=f(b)−f(a)b−a(x−a)

                                            Write P=(p,f(p)), then p∈(a,b) satisfy the equation above. Define

                                            F(x)=f(x)−f(a)−f(b)−f(a)b−a(x−a),x∈[a,b]

                                            It is easy to see that F(a)=F(b)=0, and further F(p)=0, by Roll's theorem, we can find x1∈(a,p) and x2∈(p,b) such that F′(x1)=F′(x2)=0, so we can find c∈(x1,x2) such that F″(c)=0, we have

                                            F′(x)=f′(x)−f(b)−f(a)b−a,F″(x)=f″(x)

                                            thus f″(c)=F″(c)=0.

                                            5.20

                                            If f has a finite third derivative f‴ in [a,b] and if

                                            f(a)=f′(a)=f(b)=f′(b)=0,

                                            prove that f‴(c)=0 for some c∈(a,b).

                                            Proof

                                            By Roll's theorem, there is d∈(a,b) such that f′(d)=0, thus we can find x1∈(a,d) and x2∈(d,b) such that f″(x1)=f″(x2)=0, which means we can further find c∈(x1,x2) such that f‴(c)=0.

                                            5.21

                                            Assume f is nonnegative and has a finite third derivative f‴ in the open interval (0,1). If f(x)=0 for at least two values of x in (0,1), prove that f‴(c)=0 for some c in (0,1).

                                            Proof

                                            Suppose f(a)=f(b)=0 for a,b∈(0,1), since f is nonnegative in (0,1), the point a and b are local minima of f, thus f′(a)=f′(b)=0, the conclusion follows from Exercise 5.20.

                                            5.22

                                            Assume f has a finite derivative in some interval (a,+∞).

                                            (a) If f(x)→1 and f′(x)→c as x→+∞, prove that c=0.

                                            (b) If f′(x)→1 as x→+∞, prove that f(x)/x→1 as x→+∞.

                                            (c) If f′(x)→0 as x→+∞, prove that f(x)/x→0 as x→+∞.

                                            Proof

                                            (a) Assume c≠0, then ∃G>1 such that x>G⟹|f′(x)|>c/2>0, and ∃N>G such that

                                            |f(n)−1|<1/2,∀n>N⟹|f(2n)−f(n)|<1,n>N

                                            if we choose n>N such that n>2/c, we have |f(2n)−f(n)|=|f′(ξ)|n for some ξ∈(n,2n), so we can have

                                            1=c22c<|f′(ξ)|n=|f(2n)−f(n)|<1

                                            which is a contradiction.

                                            (b) For ∀ε>0, there exist G>0 such that |f′(x)−1|<ε whenever x≥G. for any x>G, we can find some c∈(G,x) such that

                                            f(x)=f(G)+f′(c)(x−G)

                                            which means

                                            |f(x)x−1|=|f(G)x+f′(c)−1−f′(c)Gx|≤|f(G)−f′(c)Gx|+|f′(c)−1|<|f(G)|+(1+ε)Gx+ε

                                            let x→+∞, we can have

                                            |f(G)|+(1+ε)Gx<ε⟹|f(x)x−1|<2ε

                                            (c) Let g(x)=f(x)+x, then g′(x)=f′(x)+1, so g′(x)→1 as x→+∞, use (b) we can have g(x)/x→1 as x→+∞, but g(x)/x=f(x)/x+1 for ∀x∈(a,+∞), and the conclusion follows.

                                            5.23

                                            Let h be a fixed positive number. Show that there is no function f satisfying the following three conditions: f(x) exists for x≥0, f′(0)=0, f′(x)≥h for x>0.

                                            Proof

                                            That f′(0)=0 means f+′(0)=0, thus ∃δ>0 such that whenever x∈(0,δ), we have

                                            f(x)−f(0)x−0<h

                                            choose some x<δ, then there is c∈(0,x) such that f(x)−f(0)=f′(c)(x−0), then we have f′(c)<h, which is a contradiction.

                                            5.24

                                            If h>0 and if f(x) exists (and is finite) for every x in (a−h,a+h), and if f is continuous on [a−h,a+h], show that we have:

                                            (a) f(a+h)−f(a−h)h=f′(a+θh)+f′(a−θh),0<θ<1;

                                            (b) f(a+h)−2f(a)+f(a−h)h=f′(a+λh)−f′(a−λh),0<λ<1.

                                            (c) If f″(a) exists, show that f″(a)=limh→0f(a+h)−2f(a)+f(a−h)h2.

                                            (d) Give an example where the limit of the quotient in (c) exists but where f″(a) does not exist.

                                            Solution

                                            (a) Let F(x)=f(a+x)−f(a−x), then F is continuous on [0,h] and F′(x) exists in [0,h). Thus we can find c∈(0,h) such that

                                            F(h)−F(0)=f(a+h)−f(a−h)=F′(c)h=[f′(a+c)+f′(a−c)]h

                                            write c=θh, then θ∈(0,1).

                                            (b) With a similar proof of (a) by replacing F with

                                            F(x)=f(a+x)+f(a−x)−2f(a)

                                            (c) Let F be defined like (b) and G(x)=x2, by generalized Mean-Value Theorem, we can find λ∈(0,1) such that

                                            [F(x)−F(0)]G′(λx)=F′(λx)[G(x)−G(0)]

                                            which means

                                            [f(a+x)+f(a−x)−2f(a)]2λx=x2[f′(a+λx)−f′(a−λx)]

                                            or

                                            f′(a+λx)−f′(a−λx)2λx=f(a+x)+f(a−x)−2f(a)x2

                                            the conclusion follows since we can write f″(a) as

                                            f″(a)=limh→0f′(a+λh)−f′(a−λh)2λh

                                            (d) Let f(x)=x2/2 when x≥0 and −x2/2 when x<0, then for a=0, we see that f(x) exists and is continuous on [−h,h] if h>0, and

                                            limh→0f(h)−2f(0)+f(−h)h2=limh→00h2=0

                                            but

                                            f′(x)={x,x≥0−x,x<0

                                            so f+″(0)=1 and f−″(0)=−1, thus f″(0) does not exist.

                                            5.25

                                            Let f have a finite derivative in (a,b) and assume that c∈(a,b). Consider the following condition: For every ε>0 there exists a 1-ball B(c;δ), whose radius δ depends only on ε and not on c, such that if x∈B(c;δ), and x≠c, then

                                            |f(x)−f(c)x−c−f′(c)|<ε

                                            Show that f′ is continuous on (a,b) if this condition holds throughout (a,b).

                                            Solution

                                            Assume f′(x) is not continuous at some point c∈(a,b), since f′ is finite in (a,b), the discontinuity should be a jump or removable, in either case, we can find an interval (m,c) or (c,m) such that |f′(x)−f′(c)|>ε0 for some given ε0 whenever x is in the interval. For this ε0, we select the corresponding δ for the condition to hold, let δ′=min(δ,|c−m|), then if x is in the interval (c−δ′,c) or (c,c+δ′) we have

                                            |f′(x)−f′(c)|>ε0,|f(x)−f(c)x−c−f′(c)|<ε0

                                            Choose d between x and c such that

                                            f(x)−f(c)x−c=f′(d)

                                            we have |f′(d)−f′(c)|>ε0 and |f′(x)−f′(c)|<ε0, which is a contradiction.

                                            5.26

                                            Assume f has a finite derivative in (a,b) and is continuous on [a,b], with a≤f(x)≤b for all x∈[a,b] and |f′(x)|≤α<1 for all x∈(a,b). Prove that f has a unique fixed point in [a,b].

                                            Proof

                                            Let F(x)=f(x)−x, then F(a)≥0 and F(b)≤0, thus there exists c∈[a,b] such that F(c)=0 or f(c)=c. Now assume f has more than one fixed point, then ∃c1,c2∈[a,b] and F(c1)=F(c2)=0, by Roll's theorem, we can find d∈(c1,c2)⊆(a.b) such that F′(d)=f′(d)−1=0, which means f′(d)=1, but we shall have |f′(d)|<1, so we get a contradiction.

                                            5.27

                                            Give an example of a pair of functions f and g having finite derivatives in (0,1), such that

                                            limx→0f(x)g(x)=0,

                                            but such that limx→0f′(x)/g′(x) does not exist, choosing g so that g′(x) is never zero.

                                            Solution

                                            Let f(x)=x and g(x)=x2+1, then g′(x)=2x≠0 if x∈(0,1), but

                                            limx→0f(x)g(x)=limx→0xx2+1=0,limx→0f′(x)g′(x)=limx→012x

                                            which does not exist.

                                            5.28

                                            Prove the following theorem:

                                            Let f and g be two functions having finite nth derivatives in (a,b). For some interior point c in (a,b), assume that f(c)=f′(c)=⋯=f(n−1)(c)=0, and that g(c)=g′(c)=⋯=g(n−1)(c)=0, but g(n)(x) is never zero in (a,b). Show that

                                            limx→cf(x)g(x)=f(n)(c)g(n)(c).

                                            NOTE: f(n) and g(n) are not assumed to be continuous at c.

                                            Proof

                                            For any x∈(a,b) with x≠c such that g(x)≠0, apply Theorem 5.20 to f and g, we can find x1 between x and c such that

                                            [f(x)−∑k=0n−2f(k)(c)k!(x−c)k]g(n−1)(x1)=f(n−1)(x1)[g(x)−∑k=0n−2g(k)(c)k!(x−c)k]

                                            which gives f(x)g(n−1)(x1)=f(n−1)(x1)g(x), use the condition f(n−1)(c)=g(n−1)(c)=0, we can further get

                                            f(x)[g(n−1)(x1)−g(n−1)(c)]=g(x)[f(n−1)(x1)−f(n−1)(c)]

                                            notice that g(n−1)(x1)=g(n−1)(c) implies we can find some x′ between x1 and c such that g(n)(x′)=0, but g(n)(x) is never zero in (a,b) means we must have g(n−1)(x1)≠g(n−1)(c), thus the equation above can be written as

                                            f(x)g(x)=f(n−1)(x1)−f(n−1)(c)g(n−1)(x1)−g(n−1)(c)

                                            Now let x→c, then x1→c at the same time, thus

                                            limx→cf(x)g(x)=limx1→cf(n−1)(x1)−f(n−1)(c)g(n−1)(x1)−g(n−1)(c)=limx1→cf(n−1)(x1)−f(n−1)(c)x1−cg(n−1)(x1)−g(n−1)(c)x1−c=f(n)(c)g(n)(c)

                                            5.29

                                            Show that the formula in Taylor's theorem can also be written as follows:

                                            f(x)=∑k=0n−1f(k)(c)k!(x−c)k+(x−c)(x−x1)n−1(n−1)!f(n)(x1),

                                            where x1 is interior to the interval joining x and c. Let 1−θ=(x−x1)/(x−c). Show that 0<θ<1 and deduce the following form of the remainder term (due to Cauchy):

                                            (1−θ)n−1(x−c)n(n−1)!f(n)[θx+(1−θ)c].

                                            Proof

                                            Keep x fixed and define

                                            F(t)=f(t)+∑k=1n−1f(k)(t)k!(x−t)k,G(t)=g(t)=t

                                            Apply Theorem 5.12 to get x1 between x and c such that

                                            F′(x1)[G(x)−G(c)]=G′(x1)[F(x)−F(c)]

                                            which means

                                            (x−x1)n−1(n−1)!f(n)(x1)(x−c)=f(x)−f(c)−∑k=1n−1f(k)(c)k!(x−c)k

                                            since f(c)=f(c)0!(x−c)0, we get f(x) as the desired form.

                                            As

                                            1−θ=x−x1x−c⟹x1=x−(1−θ)(x−c)=θx+(1−θ)c

                                            we can have

                                            (x−c)(x−x1)n−1(n−1)!f(n)(x1)=(x−c)n(x−x1)n−1(x−c)n−1(n−1)!f(n)(x1)=(x−c)(1−θ)n−1(n−1)!f(n)[θx+(1−θ)c]
